## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Inventory of issues

Your code has **4 APIs** that won't work in .NET 8:

| API | Location | Problem in .NET 8 |
|-----|----------|--------------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Never thrown — cleanup logic is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `Stop()` | Works but wastes time — `Join` is better |

### Pattern classification

This is a **cancellable work loop** with **ThreadAbortException as control flow** and **ResetAbort to continue execution**. The replacement is `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful exit, then move on
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical changes explained

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept a `CancellationToken`.**
If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or I/O), cancellation only works if the token is forwarded:

```csharp
// Before — not cancellable, Thread.Abort was the only way to interrupt
private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// After — cooperative cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

If `GetNextItem` calls synchronous I/O that doesn't accept a token (e.g., `socket.Receive`), replace it with its async counterpart or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` around the blocking point.

**2. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent — and doesn't need one.** `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception; it does *not* auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did, so `finally` blocks run cleanly without any special call.

**3. `Thread.Sleep` → `Thread.Join`.** `Sleep(2000)` then checking `IsAlive` was a race. `Join(timeout)` blocks until the thread exits *or* the timeout elapses — strictly better.

### Common pitfalls for this specific code

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Forgetting to pass `token` into `GetNextItem` | The loop will hang at the blocking call forever — `Cancel()` won't wake it up. This is the #1 cause of "cancellation doesn't work" bugs. |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timer/callback registrations. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter shown above so you don't accidentally swallow unrelated cancellations from inner code. |
| Assuming `Cancel()` stops the thread instantly | Cooperative cancellation only triggers at the next checkpoint (`Take(token)`, `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`). If `ProcessItem` is long-running, consider passing the token into it too. |
